{
  "python-envs.defaultEnvManager": "ms-python.python:system",
  /*
  Goal:
  Define which Python environment VS Code should use to run the project.

  Logic:
  - Use the system Python (installed on your computer)
  - Do not create or use a virtual environment

  Why this matters:
  Python projects can run in different environments.
  If not configured correctly:
  → dependencies may not work
  → code may fail to run

  Example:
  If your system Python is:
  /usr/bin/python3

  Then VS Code will use this interpreter automatically
  for running and analyzing your code.
  */


  "python.analysis.extraPaths": ["./src"]
  /*
  Goal:
  Help VS Code correctly find and understand your project modules.

  Logic:
  - Add "./src" as an additional search path
  - This allows imports like:
        from src.learning.module import function
    to work correctly inside the editor

  Problem this solves:
  Without this setting:
  → VS Code does not know where "src" is
  → it shows errors like:
        "Module not found"

  Example:

  Project structure:
  project/
    ├── src/
    │     ├── learning/
    │     ├── database/
    │     └── config/
    ├── app.py

  Code:
      from src.learning.correction_memory import get_pattern_summary

  Without this setting:
      ❌ Import error

  With this setting:
      ✅ Import works correctly (VS Code understands it)

  Important note:
  This setting ONLY affects VS Code (editor behavior):
  - autocomplete
  - linting
  - error highlighting

  It does NOT affect actual execution.

  For runtime execution:
  You must still define:
      export PYTHONPATH=$(pwd)

  This ensures Python itself can locate the "src" folder.
  */
}